">News</span></a></div><div itemscope itemtype="http://data-vocabulary.org/Breadcrumb" class="lft pathone"><a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/archive" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="title">Archive</span></a></div><div itemscope itemtype="http://data-vocabulary.org/Breadcrumb" class="lft pathone"><a itemprop="url" href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/section/150/1/the-big-story.html"><span itemprop="title">The Big Story</span></a></div><div itemscope itemtype="http://data-vocabulary.org/Breadcrumb" class="lft pathfour"><a itemprop="url pathfour" href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/Issue?issueId=1536"><span itemprop="title">January 18, 2016</span></a></div></div></div><div class="clr"></div><div class="fixedsocial"><ul><li class="facbook"><a href="https://facebook.com/sharer.php?u=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/amit-shah-bjp-the-steep-climb-ahead/1/564316.html" onClick="return popup(this, 'notes')" data-value-share="Facebook">facbook</a></li><li class="twitter"><a href='https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/amit-shah-bjp-the-steep-climb-ahead/1/564316.html&amp;text=The steep climb ahead&amp;via=indiatoday' onClick="return popup(this, 'notes')" data-value-share="Twitter">twitter</a></li><li class="googlepluse"><a onClick="javascript:window.open(this.href,'', 'menubar=no,toolbar=no,resizable=yes,scrollbars=yes,height=600,width=600');return false;" href="https://plus.google.com/share?url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/amit-shah-bjp-the-steep-climb-ahead/1/564316.html" data-value-share="Google">googlepluse</a></li><script type="text/javascript">
	ajaxinclude("/rss/chunk_story_sharecount.jsp?createddate=2016-01-06&shareUrl=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/amit-shah-bjp-the-steep-climb-ahead/1/564316.html&sid=564316")
	</script></ul></div><div class="strleft"><h1>The steep climb ahead</h1><div class="strtitlealias"><h2><p>An electoral strategist, a grassroots level manager and an organisational man, Amit Shah faces his biggest test during the assembly elections in 2016</p></h2></div><div class="divclear"></div><div class="newstory-stripsection clearfix"><div class="author-section clearfix"><div class="author-img"><img src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/homenew/defaultauthor-img.gif" width="44" alt=""></div><div class="autherninfo"><div class="authername"><a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/author/Uday-Mahurkar/1.html">Uday Mahurkar</a><span id="arrowclick"><span class="arrow"></span></span></div><div id="auther-shortinfo"> &nbsp;<a href="https://twitter.com/@UdayMahurkar" target="_blank" class="twitter-follow-button" data-show-count="false" data-lang="en">Follow @UdayMahurkar</a>&nbsp; &nbsp;<a href="mailto:uday.mahurkar@gmail.com">uday.mahurkar@gmail.com</a></div><div class="story-timedate"> January 6, 2016&nbsp;| UPDATED&nbsp;16:08 IST </div></div></div><div class="font-incer"><div class="size_inc_dec"><a href="javascript:increaseFontSize();">A +</a><a href="javascript:decreaseFontSize();">A -</a></div></div></div><div class="divclear"></div><div class="mediumcontent"><div class='strcaptxt'><div class='divleft'><div class='downloadstoryimg'><div class='storyimgclose'><div class="loadmore_bg" onclick="ga('send', 'event', 'Story Page Expand Image', 'click','Story Page Expand Image', 1, {'nonInteraction': 1});return true;"></div><img src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories/amit-shah-jan18-1_647_010716074944.jpg" width='647' align='middle' alt="Amit Shah" title="Amit Shah"/><span class="stimagecaption">Amit Shah at the 'Karyakarta Maha Sammelan' (workers' meet) in Jaipur in April 2015. Photo: Purushottam Diwakar</span></div></div></div></div><div class='clear'></div><div class="divclear"></div><div class="right-story-container" style="width: 100%;"><p>Like most Shakespearean heroes, BJP president Amit Shah, whose tenure is up for renewal this month, has a vaulting ambition. But in Shakespearean tragedies, the protagonist's one major fault, say hubris, at times leads to his fall. In Shah's case it is even taller than his ambition, according to his detractors. As a result, this crafty Chanakya of BJP politics, who is still riding the crest of his career and is likely to become party president for the second-term, has begun a slide downwards in the second half of his first-term-witness the consecutive losses of the BJP in the assembly elections of Delhi and Bihar.</p><p>Moreover, the challenges of his second-term presidency are likely to be tougher than that of his first-term. The BJP is at a disadvantage in a majority of the seven states-Kerala, Tamil Nadu, West Bengal, Assam, Puducherry, Punjab and Uttar Pradesh-scheduled to go to polls in 2016 and 2017. The important question is, will his attitude trump ambition, or the other way round? Will the second-term prove to be a steep climb ahead? Will Shah be faced with second-term blues? Will Shah continue to remain the Shahenshah?</p><p><b>As an organiser</b><br/>Consider a report card on Shah's first-term as president of the party. Electorally, it is mixed. He began his presidency with a string of four astonishing victories in a row: Maharashtra, Haryana, Jharkhand and Jammu and Kashmir. In the first two, the BJP under Shah's leadership, defeated Congress incumbents boasting the pursuit of a 'Congress mukht Bharat' (Congress free India). Jharkhand has had a BJP government in the past. The BJP penetrated J&amp;K for the first time and ended up stitching an out-of-the-box coalition government. Critics dismiss the triumphs as an outcome of the Modi wave.</p><p>Victory leads to arrogance and arrogance to defeat. Soon the tide turned against the BJP. Delhi and Bihar were stunning setbacks. Shah has been blamed in both cases by his detractors of marginalising local leaders and relying on outsiders. While in Delhi, Kiran Bedi was imposed from above during mid-campaign, in Bihar, Shah totally relied on a coterie of non-Bihari leaders. The strategy backfired leading to a humiliating defeat.</p><p><div class="storycentimg" style='border:0px solid #d7d7d7; margin:0 ; width:100%; float:left'><div style='width:100%'><img src='http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories//2016January/amitsmall1_010716075153.jpg' align='left' alt='' title='' style='border:1px solid #d7d7d7; margin:2px 0px'></div><div class='clicktoenlarge' style='width:100% text-align:center' valign='bottom'><a href='#' onClick="javascript:window.open('http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story_image.jsp?img=/images/stories/2016January/amitlarge1_010716075153.jpg&caption=','window','status=no,resize=yes,toolbar=no,scrollbars=yes,width=1221,height=216'); return false;">Click here to Enlarge</a></div></div>Two consecutive defeats in key states led to intense factionalism within the BJP. Dissidents and rebels became the enemy within. They openly questioned the top leadership led by Shah and Modi. All of a sudden the massive party enrolment drive led by Shah began appearing "fake". Senior BJP leaders questioned Shah's inaccessibility and even raised disturbing questions about the rise of a three-man coterie-Modi, Shah and Jaitley-within the party attempting to crush all democratic dissidence.</p><p>Shah's slate, however, looks better as an organiser. He undertook an ambitious membership drive in 2015 and with the help of emails, missed calls and other digital techniques claimed to have registered 11 crore workers. The programme drew flak from Shah's detractors. They claimed a majority of registered members were fake. Shah disagrees. "The allegations of fake members is utterly baseless. We are working with a long-term and solid vision and not a short-term one with an eye on publicity," he says. Bihar is the best barometer. The party got 86 lakhs votes in the 2015 assembly elections with a cadre base of 60 lakh.</p><p><b>A grassroots level leader</b><br/>Shah's organisational strength lies in his ability to give more prominence to grassroot level workers compared to power brokers within the party. Despite being accused of encouraging coterie politics by his critics, this subaltern approach helps Shah in spotting the best and most sincere party workers. Each programme of the party-building exercise ranges from half a day at the tehsil level to four days at the national level. The programmes include an exhibition on party history, the stories of former leaders and key campaigns of the past. Says K.G. Balakrishnan, former editor of RSS mouthpiece Organiser and a leader involved closely with the training programme, "Nothing is amiss in the programme. How to generate funds for the party at the state level is also included. It is a foundation laying programme as we expect this to produce party workers with a missionary zeal."</p><p><b>As a party balancer</b><br/>Shah is often criticised by senior leaders for being inaccessible. Two former national general secretaries, one of them being Balbir Punj, have failed to get an appointment with Shah for over a year despite more than two attempts. Shah has also failed, according to his detractors, in maintaining a balance between the two rival factions of the party-the <a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/people/arun-jaitley/19435.html"><img class="pf_img" src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories/arun_041515061234.jpg" width="30" height="30" alt=""/>Arun Jaitley</a> camp versus the dissidents. Ideologues such as Arun Shourie have been completely marginalised much to the chagrin of RSS leaders.</p><p>Says Shourie, "Shah is a party loyalist and also the only leader truly loyal to Modi. Even if it meant convincing Modi, Shah shouldn't have allowed a situation where the impression goes that only a few are running the party organisation. It will do great long-term damage to the organisation if Shah doesn't do the balancing act".</p><p><div class="storycentimg" style='border:0px solid #d7d7d7; margin:0 ; width:100%; float:left'><div style='width:100%'><img src='http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories//2016January/amit2_010716075241.jpg' align='left' alt='Amit Shah, <a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/people/narendra-modi/17737.html"><img class="pf_img" src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories/modi_042215023911.jpg" width="30" height="30" alt=""/>Narendra Modi</a>' title='Amit Shah, Narendra Modi' style='border:1px solid #d7d7d7; margin:2px 0px'></div><h2 class='mos-caption' style='width:100%; text-align:center'>Narendra Modi with Amit Shah at a BJP Parliamentary Party meeting in July 2015. Photo: Yasbant Negi</h2></div>Another general secretary who Shah has refused to meet says, "I find it odd that some who used to criticise BJP openly in the past are now part of the BJP mainstream and people like me and Arun Shourie, who have always been ideologically most committed, are treated as outsiders."</p><p>Party secretary Shrikant Sharma defends Shah against such allegations, "Adhyakshji not meeting senior leaders is unlikely. But ultimately these are small issues. The significant issue is that the BJP will be a new party under him. He has a vision of 50 years down the line for the party. He is building district units in all the 600 districts with well-equipped library and training 15 lakh party workers in ideology, commitment and discipline. Few party presidents in the past have ever met so many party workers on a day-to-day basis like Shah."</p><p><b>An election strategist</b><br/>No party president-whether <a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/people/rajnath-singh/19434.html"><img class="pf_img" src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories/rajnath_041515061307.jpg" width="30" height="30" alt=""/>Rajnath Singh</a>, <a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/people/nitin-gadkari/19436.html"><img class="pf_img" src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories/gadkari_041515061156.jpg" width="30" height="30" alt=""/>Nitin Gadkari</a>, not even Lal Krishna Advani-has been as astute an election strategist as Amit Shah. When the tickets for the 2014 Lok Sabha polls were being finalised, the then general secretary in-charge of UP, Shah got a golden rule for ticket-distribution cleared from the top party leadership. Tickets would be given only to those candidates staying in constituencies for which they sought a ticket. An exception would be made only in the case of a few seniormost leaders. Despite intense pressure to break the rule, Shah stuck to the criteria and made exceptions in just a few cases, including <a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/people/kalraj-mishra/19442.html"><img class="pf_img" src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories/kalraj_041515060742.jpg" width="30" height="30" alt=""/>Kalraj Mishra</a> and <a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/people/hema-malini/19525.html"><img class="pf_img" src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories/hema_041515033650.jpg" width="30" height="30" alt=""/>Hema Malini</a>.</p><p>Amongst those who failed to secure a ticket was Siddharthnath Singh, a Jaitley acolyte, who was seeking ticket from Phulpur, a constituency he never lived in. Despite intense pressure to accommodate Singh, Shah did not relent. Shah's firmness during the UP Lok Sabha election is considered as the main factor responsible for the BJP's grand victory.</p><p>Other than firmness, Shah gave 50 per cent of the tickets to OBC candidates. Most of these were not imports from outside but Sangh Parivar loyalists. Says political analyst Vidyut Thakar, "What happened in UP is one of the biggest socio-political changes in the BJP. Shah brought back the old Brahmin-Bania leadership of BJP that had become inactive. Additionally, he gave 50 per cent tickets to OBC candidates who were BJP loyalists." Will this formula work in the 2017 assembly polls remains an open question.</p><p>But the Bihar assembly election in 2015 proved Shah's waterloo. Unlike UP 2014, local leaders were sidelined in Bihar 2015. The campaign was run with the help of a small, inexperienced group of non-Bihari leaders. Shah committed the mistake of running the campaign with just two faces on the posters-Prime Minister Modi and himself-both non-Biharis, both Gujaratis. The BJP paid a heavy price. Bihar Chief Minister <a href="http://indiatoday.intoday.in/people/nitish-kumar/17944.html"><img class="pf_img" src="http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories/nitish_042215020619.jpg" width="30" height="30" alt=""/>Nitish Kumar</a> beat the two outsiders with his campaign slogan of Biharis versus Baharis (outsiders).</p><p>According to Shah's critics, negative campaigning, the use of sectarian images and Shah's arrogance equally contributed to the party's humiliating defeat in Bihar. Shah's comment, "If voters vote for our rivals, crackers will be burst in Pakistan," boomeranged on the BJP. Says Nishit Vyas, Gujarat Congress general secretary, who has known Shah for a long time, "One of the things that Shah is paying the price for is certainly arrogance."</p><p>Ditto in Delhi. Shah, under pressure from Modi and Jaitley, sidelined Dr Harshvardhan by imposing super-cop Kiran Bedi, an outsider, as the party's chief ministerial candidate. The party paid an equally heavy price by being reduced to a paltry three seats out of 70.</p><p><div class="storycentimg" style='border:0px solid #d7d7d7; margin:0 ; width:100%; float:left'><div style='width:100%'><img src='http://media2.intoday.in/indiatoday/images/stories//2016January/amit3_010716075459.jpg' align='left' alt='' title='' style='border:1px solid #d7d7d7; margin:2px 0px'></div></div>According to a party source, some NDA ministers from the Modi cabinet, who campaigned in Bihar were so miffed with both Shah and Modi, due to their non-consultative style of functioning, that they used to freely exchange information with the Nitish Kumar camp. In a few cases, they even managed to get meals from the JD(U) camp while campaigning. Party national general secretary Bhupendra Yadav disagrees, "Shah never abandoned the consultative process at any stage," says Yadav. "Shah's attempts to build the party organisation is unprecedented. It will certainly produce results as the army of missionary workers are entering the political field. An average party worker has high hopes from Shah."</p><p>Shah's great electoral skills were on display in the four assembly elections of Maharashtra, Jharkhand, Haryana and Jammu and Kashmir, all of which were held before the Delhi and Bihar defeats. The Bihar defeat was due to the index of opposition unity. Says Shrikant Sharma, " We got only 5 per cent less votes in Bihar than the Lok Sabha polls and the votes of our allies didn't get transferred to us. In Haryana too we got less votes than in the Lok Sabha. Yet we won in Haryana but lost Bihar. Main reason is because of a united opposition." The trouble is the Bihar template of opposition unity might be tested in future assembly polls. That will be the main electoral challenge for Shah's leadership of the BJP. Unless BJP wins one of these states, Shah's leadership is bound to face a serious challenge from within the BJP.</p><p><b>The Modi-Shah symbiosis</b><br/>Shah's biggest strength within the BJP is his close proximity to Modi. The two have worked together since the late 1980s, when Modi, an RSS pracharak, entered the BJP through the RSS and Shah was a junior party worker. The proximity to Modi is both an advantage as well as a disadvantage, according to insiders. Modi, as a slave driver, is known to extract more than his subordinates can give like the adage when the going gets tough, the tough get going. Under such exacting standards, only the tough Shah can survive. The friendship between the two has evolved over the long-term. The two have implemented many strategies together in the past two decades. Besides, Shah, after he shifted to Delhi, did the best defence of Modi on TV channels against the attacks of the rivals, whether by Congress leaders or left NGOs on the 2002 Godhra issue or on the fake encounter cases in Gujarat. Says Shankarbhai Chaudhary, a minister in the Anandiben ministry in Gujarat, who knows both Shah and Modi closely, "Few understand Narendrabhai's mind as Amitbhai does. It is a symbiotic relationship."</p><p>A is for ambition. A is for Amit Shah. If the ambition of Shah trumps his style, then Shah might turn the party around and lead it to victory in some of the key states as well as in the country in 2019. However, if Shah's demeanour takes the better of his ambition, then like Shakespearean tragedies, the BJP might hurtle towards one defeat after another. And Shah might find himself on a slippery slope.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><div align="right"><i><b>Follow the writer on Twitter @UdayMahurkar</b></i></div><p>&nbsp;</p></div></div><div class="divclear"></div><p class="more-news"> For more news from India Today, follow us on Twitter <a style="font-weight: normal" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="https://twitter.com/indiatoday">@indiatoday</a> and on Facebook at <a style="font-weight: normal" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="https://www.facebook.com/IndiaToday">facebook.com/IndiaToday</a><br><span style="padding-top: 10px; display: inline-block"> For news and videos in Hindi, go to <a target="_blank" rel="nofollow" href="http://aajtak.intoday.in">AajTak.in</a>. ताज़ातरीन ख़बरों और वीडियो के लिए <a rel="nofollow" target="_blank" href="http://aajtak.intoday.in">आजतक.इन</a> पर आएं.</span></p><div class="clear"> &nbsp; </div><script type="text/javascript">
